# Sacrum

> The sacrum is a **triangular flat bone** formed by the fusion of **5 sacral vertebrae**. It sits at the base of the spine, wedged between the two hip bones to form the **posterior pelvis**.

## 🔗 Connected Structures
- [[Lumbar Vertebrae]] — L5 articulates at the **lumbosacral joint (L5/S1)**
- [[Coccyx]] — Sacral apex articulates with the coccyx at the **sacrococcygeal joint**
- [[Hip Bone]] — Bilateral articulation at the **sacroiliac joint (SIJ)**

## 🔗 Associated Muscles
- [[Gluteus Maximus]] — Originates from the posterior sacrum and ilium
- [[Erector Spinae]] — Attaches to the sacral crest

## 🗂️ Structure

| Part | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Base | Superior; L5 articulation; anterior projection = **sacral promontory** |
| Apex | Inferior; articulates with coccyx |
| Pelvic surface | Concave; 4 pairs of anterior sacral foramina |
| Dorsal surface | Convex; 4 pairs of posterior sacral foramina; median sacral crest |
| Auricular surface | Bilateral; forms the sacroiliac joint |

## 🔑 Sacral Foramina
- 4 pairs each (anterior and posterior)
- Transmit **sacral nerves S1–S4**
- S2–S4: parasympathetic innervation to bladder, rectum, and genitalia

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Sacroiliitis** — Early lesion in ankylosing spondylitis
- **Sacral fractures** — High-energy trauma or insufficiency fractures in the elderly
- **Coccydynia** — Tailbone pain after falls or childbirth
- **Caudal epidural anesthesia** — Accessed through the sacral hiatus
- **Obstetrics** — True conjugate determines pelvic inlet adequacy


